arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The collection is arranged as received by the Rockefeller Archive Center, in two subgroups.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Stacy May (b.1896-d.1980) was born in Philadelphia in 1896. He attended Amherst College and received his Ph.D. in economics from the Brookings Graduate School of Economics and Government in Washington, D.C. in 1925.

He taught economics at Amherst, Cornell and Dartmouth in the 1920s and early 1930s. May was assistant director of Social Sciences at the Rockefeller Foundation from 1932-1942. May was the Director of the Bureau of Research and Statistics of the War Production Board from 1940-1944 and he served as an economic analyst for several government advisory committees and commission. During his career he was also an economist for McGraw Hill Publishing.

From 1947-1962, May served as economic advisor to Room 5600, the Rockefeller family office, and to the International Basic Economy Corporation (IBEC), where he worked on the economic development of Latin America, Africa and Asia. He retired in 1965 as an economic consultant to the Rockefeller family.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Records were initially processed while the collection was under the care of the University of Wyoming, prior to transfer to RAC. Records received further processing at the RAC.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: The Stacy May papers were donated and transferred to the Rockefeller Archive Center by the Univerity of Wyoming (Laramie).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The collection documents May's career as an economist. Most materials are dated after 1947 and pertain to his work with the Rockefellers.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Subgroup 1 is open for research. Subgroup 2 remains restricted from research pending further processing.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Information regarding the Rockefeller Archive Center's preferred elements and forms of citation can be found at http://www.rockarch.org/research/citations.php

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Materials include:
Professional Correspondence Files, 1919-1971 - Contains Rockefeller related material, travels plans, etc.
Speeches and Addresses, 1940-1971 - By May and others.

Subject Files - Contain correspondence, memos, speeches, notes receipts and secondary material such as pamphlets and reprints. Topics include: Advisory Boards and Committees; Kennedy Administration Actions: Reports and memos on Kennedy's economics vs. Rockefeller's, 1961; Includes original report by May submitted to Rockefeller.Nelson A. Rockefeller - Contains original drafts of speeches prepared by May for Rockefeller on economic issues; also contains conference material, memos and reports on economic matters. New York - Contains memos, correspondence, reports and handwritten drafts on economics and industry in New York.
United Fruit Company - Correspondence about an article written by May for Fortune Magazine, and letters regarding labor and management.
Rockefeller Brothers Fund, Special Studies Project.
Notebooks related to Rockefeller Work.
Human Resources File: Rockefeller Foundation job applications and correspondence.
Stacy May Personal Files, 1930s - Contains material not pertaining to work with Rockefeller Foundation; addresses and speeches he gave at colleges, letters to students.
National Planning Association Files, 1944-1957.
Photos.
Reports - By May and others.
Manuscripts by others/or unknown author.
Bank Statements, Receipts.
Booklets and Pamphlets - Pertaining to economic issues in the United States and globally.
Government Reports - Primarily consisting of Department of Commerce, Department of Labor, Special Studies Reports, Congressional Reports.
Newspapers, Periodicals and Reprints.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Although the acronym "DNA" may have stood for Definitive News Analysis, no corroboration has been found in the written record. The staff of DNA were on Rockefeller's personal payroll. There were two main divisions to DNA, a research group for Nelson A. Rockefeller. The Domestic Policy staff was overseen by Roswell B. Perkins, while the Foreign Policy staff was led by Henry Kissinger. In later years, DNA was headed by Oscar M. Ruebhausen. The main function of the organization was to draft position papers and research reports on issues important to Rockefeller's pursuit of the Republican presidential nomination. Source: Scope and Content Note, Nelson A. Rockefeller papers, DNA, Series G (FA342)
